  m_Name: DialogNPCEngineer
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  Name: Hasan al-Rumeli
  Icon: {fileID: 1911240704, guid: 5fde7217974c70442be62433a1902ed2, type: 3}
  HasInteraction: 0
  interactionType: 1
  Greeting: Yahya Lab11
  Day1Dialog: []
  Day2FirstTimeDialog: []
  Day2MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day3FirstTimeDialog: []
  Day3MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day4FirstTimeDialog: []
  Day4MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day5FirstTimeDialog: []
  Day5MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day6Dialog:
  - 'St. Elmo is a textbook star fort. Low walls, angled bastions, fields of fire
    designed to punish haste. I walked the lines today and marked where the guns
    must speak and where the earth must be cut. The men believe the fort will fall
    because we are many. I know it will fall because geometry always wins.


    By
    tomorrow, I expect the first corrections to begin.'
  Day7FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'The bombardment proceeds as planned, but the fort answers more stubbornly than
    expected. Their guns are fewer, yet placed with care.

    Every advance costs
    more time than the drawings predicted. The theory remains sound.


    By tomorrow,
    I fear reality will demand payment in ways the plans do not record.'
  Day7MetBeforeDialog:
  - Yesterday, I explained why patience mattered.  Today the men wanted speed, they
    asked why the walls still stand when the guns have spoken all day. I pointed
    to angles, to depth, to stone that first must be emptied of strength. By tomorrow,
    I will realize that explanation does not lessen the waiting.
  Day8FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'We advance the batteries closer. Saps deepen. Earth collapses. Men dig again.
    Every measurement is precise; every outcome is slower than expected.

    I watch
    bodies carried past trenches I designed to protect them.


    By tomorrow, I
    fear I will stop pretending this delay is merely technical.'
  Day8MetBeforeDialog:
  - 'Today, an assault went forward before the breach was ready. The fort responded
    exactly as it was built to do. The losses were predictable. That is what unsettles
    me most. I did not argue; I adjusted the plan afterward.


    By tomorrow, I
    will know that knowledge does not grant authority, only responsibility.'
  Day9FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'The walls show weakness now. Cracks appear where the geometry finally fails.
    Victory feels close enough to touch. And yet, the cost has exceeded every calculation
    I made.


    By tomorrow, I fear I will stop counting men and count only progress.'
  Day9MetBeforeDialog:
  - 'A soldier asked me why St. Elmo still matters if the rest of the island waits.
    I told him that forts are lessons: if one resists, others gain courage.

    He
    nodded, as if that made sense of the dead.


    By tomorrow, I suspect I will
    stop offering reasons and speak only in orders.'
  Day10FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Today, the camp changed shape without moving.\nDragut is dead.\nThe guns still
    point where I placed them, the trenches still follow my lines \u2014 but certainty
    has fractured. For the first time, the fort feels less like a problem to solve
    and more like a warning.\n\nBy tomorrow, I fear I will understand that mastery
    does not protect you from consequence."
  Day10MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Dragut died today. The man who trusted the mathematics of siege as much as I
    did is gone. The plans remain correct. The fort will fall.\n\nAnd yet, standing
    before the battered walls, I feel no satisfaction \u2014 only the weight of knowing
    exactly how much this knowledge has cost.\n\nBy tomorrow, if the breach is taken,
    I will know that understanding a fortress completely does not spare you from
    being haunted by the path you chose to open."
